	(601,782,X'',X'3C6272202F3E',X'3C6272202F3E',NULL,'\n MILLENNIUM BROADWAY HOTEL, NEW YORK\n\n  \n\n Hudson Theatre, the only Broadway Theatre which is regularly available for concerts, meetings, weddings and other events. The Hudson Theatre is the second oldest theatre in New York and celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2003.  Stars such as Barbra Streisand and Louis Armstrong made their debuts at the Hudson Theatre, and the Tonight Show with Steve Allen first aired on that very same stage.','\n MILLENNIUM BROADWAY HOTEL, NEW YORK\n\n  \n\n Hudson Theatre, the only Broadway Theatre which is regularly available for concerts, meetings, weddings and other events. The Hudson Theatre is the second oldest theatre in New York and celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2003.  Stars such as Barbra Streisand and Louis Armstrong made their debuts at the Hudson Theatre, and the Tonight Show with Steve Allen first aired on that very same stage.',X'','','',''),
	(602,783,X'',X'3C6272202F3E',X'3C6272202F3E',NULL,'\n Raimundtheater\n The Raimund Theater was founded in 1893 as counterpart to the bourgeois theatres at the centre of Vienna. At the beginning of the 20th century it developed into one of Vienna\'s great places for operettas. Since the 1980s it has been one of this city\'s most famous show grounds for musical extravaganza.','\n Raimundtheater\n The Raimund Theater was founded in 1893 as counterpart to the bourgeois theatres at the centre of Vienna. At the beginning of the 20th century it developed into one of Vienna\'s great places for operettas. Since the 1980s it has been one of this city\'s most famous show grounds for musical extravaganza.',X'','','',''),
	(387,411,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Date visited:  6/2/1994 n                                    Country:   Italy  Sicily n                                     Period:   Roman nName of theatre: Teatro Romano di Tauromenion nCity, @ or near: Taormina nn  Approximate location: On E coast midway between Messina and Catania. n     Alternative names:  nn+Research Value:  4 nNotes:  This theatre was converted to an amphiteatre but it still retains the most extensive skene structures to be found anywhere. nnBibliography:  Coarelli, Filippo and Mario Torelli. Sicilia. Vol. 13. of Guide Archeologiche Laterza.  edt. Filippo Coarelli.  Rome; Gius, Laterza & Figli Spa, 1980. plan 360, 359 363, odeon 363 4. On file n   nBuilt    :     nExcavated:     nRestorations:  n  Notes:  nDirection stage faces: NE  The audience faced Etna, which they should have been able to see through the central door. The colonnade at the back of the theatre overlooks a cliff which is right on the Ionia sea  check this.nEstimated seating capacity:  this is a very large theatre. nDescription:  The skene here is especially complex. First, there is a vaulted passageway behind it that is lower than the orchestra level. This must date to the conversion to an arena. The vaulting is so low because the doors of the skene were at a higher level and actually opened out onto the roof of this passagway so you had a set of Arena entrances surmounted by a set of stage entrances. The wall behind this vaulted passageway shows that there were thresholds at the stage door level so that when the central door was open on the skene the audience saw through it, across the roof of the vaulted passage way through the rear wall behind, across the access passage way at theatre  level to a spectacular vista of Etna. Mama mia! The central door is 7\'6\" wide at arena level. The side doors are 6\' wide at arena level. 41\'6\" separate the central door from the doors on each side.  n  Notes:  There is an odeon here with 9 10 rows of seating visible (rise over run = 13/23 with footrest 13/11.5. A church is on the stage which would have faced SW. When the big theatres went over to arenas the odeons meet the needs of theatrical performances. My measuring devises were dead when we got in to this space, by the time we found batteries and returned the odeon was locked. nnHow to get there:n  nn    Height of stage:  No longer exsists but judging from the likly location of the doors in the skene it musthave been high.  n    Width of stage:   The skene is 133\' wide, the stage should have been aboutthe same. n    Depth of stage:   30\' measued from paradoi to skene frons. n    Curtain trench:   non  Distance from rear of front wall to face ofn                        second wall.nn    Arena width:   111\' n    Arena radius:  100\'  measured from skene central door to row of stones underthe bleechers that seems to indicate circomference of original circle.nn    Pluteus height:    non nn    Auditorium width:   n    Tiers #:   Rows/tier 1.    2.   3.  n        Full rows:    to     Partial rows:    to   n        Notes:nn    Seating: rise/run. Footrest:  /    1.  13 / 30  2.  /  nI did not measure the amount of seating space vs the amount of walkway in the 30\" run here but what is interesting is that the walkway is dirt and not stone. That suggests that the seating is terraced into the earthen hillside and then stones only large enough for sitting on are put in place. In other theatres the stones have the seat plus the walkway plus a few inches for the front end  of the next row to rest on.nnTauromenium (modern Taormina- Italy). Cavea width: 109 m- orchestra width: 28 m; capacity: 8-900/11-150; ca. 265-215 BC.','Date visited:  6/2/1994 n                                    Country:   Italy  Sicily n                                     Period:   Roman nName of theatre: Teatro Romano di Tauromenion nCity, @ or near: Taormina nn  Approximate location: On E coast midway between Messina and Catania. n     Alternative n